As we will see in a later chapter that in a very unwise strategic move one of the Group Presidents in the 90s decided to stop funding research for the division, and let it die off. It did not take long for the company to realize it was a bad move and to reverse it. That President did not last long.

While the Group quit selling 900 series modules in the 70s, you found them still in racks at the turn of the century. The 7700 series that replaced the 900, and then 8500 series introduced in 85 were common until about 10 years ago. In 1998 the first HD series modules, the MAX 9000, were introduced. The company sells modules to this day. But now they are a mix of products developed by the Group itself, and ones developed by others that were competitors, but now also bear the Grass Valley name.

<h2>Wavelink</h2>
The first Olympic Games televised in the U.S. were the 1960 Winter Olympics from Squaw Valley (Lake Tahoe, not far from Grass Valley) and the Summer Olympics in Rome. These were done by CBS. CBS paid almost nothing for the rights at the Tahoe venue and paid only half a million for the games in Rome. In the Winter games, during a men's slalom event, CBS allowed officials to review tape of one of the runs, to determine if a skier had missed a gate. This gave CBS the idea for instant replay, which was debuted in anything resembling its present form in 1965.

As we saw earlier, was that ABC, as the third network in a three network race back in the early 60s, had aggressively gone after sports as a way to delineate themselves. As we saw they couldn't outspend the other two, but they innovated, and when the chance to get the 1964 Innsbruck Winter Olympics presented itself, for over a half million dollars instead of the $50K CBS spent for the 1960 Winter Olympics, ABC jumped at it. They had lured legionary sportscaster Jim McKay who covered the Olympics for CBS to ABC in 1961, and with the production staff ABC had put together for their Wide World of Sports franchise, they were uniquely qualified to make a go of it. Technology being what it was at the time the 16,5 hours of coverage was videotaped, in black and white, and flown back to the states. Luckily most events at Innsbruck were in the morning, giving enough time given the seven hour time difference between Austria and the east coast of the U.S. for the events to be flown back and aired that evening.

The Geo-synchronous satellite for television use was still a few years away, so the only live event aired in the states was a 15 minute window of the closing ceremonies provided by the Telstar satellite, launched in 1962, which had to be tracked as it passed over Europe.

ABC held onto the Olympics until 1988, and then lost the rights to NBC. The last Winter Olympics ABC aired cost them over three hundred million dollars.

As the book has mentioned a number of times, ABC often looked to the Group as their engineering arm. As we looked at a short while ago, ABC was pushing for another innovation for the 1980 Olympics, the 300 switcher. ABC also presented a special project on top of the mess that was the 300, they asked the Group to develop a system to send video down fiber optics for use at the 80 Olympics. While extremely common today, it was a novel idea inside the television industry in the late 70s.

Eric Rosenthal of ABC Engineering asked Birney Dayton to head up the fiber project for those Olympics to solve the "long run" problem. The Winter Olympics required cameras placed high up on mountains to cover the ski runs. These could literally require runs of well over a mile. Sending analog video down coax cables, would not cut it. The only other way to get camera video off the mountain was with microwaves. Microwave gear was expensive, and still not very portable, and most importantly required line of site. Often not possible in these settings, and many paths would require multiple links to get it where it needed to go.

In addition, ABC prided themselves in firsts. Peter Cervalic of ABC connived for the Group's system to be used for the opening ceremony, which would make it the first fiber system ever to carry video, even though AT&T had a fiber link back to New York City.

**********************************************************************
