<h2>Routers</h2>'
https://www.lomaricatv.com/preview/chapters/graphics/70-6%20ABC%201800%20router.jpg
The Group built a special "one of" product for ABC back in 1970, the 1800 television router. As we have mentioned what TV folks typically referred to as a router, is what the computer folks call a switch. Here Bill Rhorden discusses 1800 assembly issues with the lead assembler. The 1800 was the first video and audio router.

By the time the television industry started making "routers," the switch term had already been given as the root part of switcher. Eventually the computer industry ended up co-opting these terms. Today television production switchers often have built in routers, it is not visa-versa, as dedicated video routers do not have production switchers built in, not yet. But one thing for sure is that as time goes on more and more things that were separate and dedicated to a specific function become combined in multi-function boxes.

By 1975 the Group were offering routers, but most were still fairly customized for the particular customer. These routers were known as the 3600, and the 3200 "compact" router. (Any background on these?)

We mentioned earlier that if a video switcher went totally down, while it would be a very bad day, the fall back is usually the video router. While a router cannot add effects, it would be able to get the necessary sources to air. If the router went down, the day is an unmitigated disaster. Large television routers have always been "enterprise" devices. A facility depends on them. They must be built to last and be fail proof.

Starting with the router's power supply. It has to have a 20 year life as that might be as long as the router is in service. In most computers they only have a three year lifetime expectancy cycle. We have already talked a bit about heat in electronic equipment. Heat plays an important role not only in router reliability. Heat has a major effect on signal integrity, increasing signal noise, and decreasing signal stability. Airflow and heat density also affect long-term reliability, as the hotter the electronics are, the shorter their lifespan. Designers strive to create sufficient internal airflow and low-power consumption which ensures cooler operation. Localized hot spots inside gear, where heat density is too great for the airflow provided, will increase stress on internal components. Something as ubiquitous as muffin fans for cooling can lead to catastrophic failure. As fans age, they slow up, and eventually fail. The cheap ones do that much sooner.

As signals have gone up in frequency from analog to standard definition digital, high definition, and now 4K, the heat generated by processing these signals has gone up as the frequency has gone up. Yes even with digital, we worry about the frequency. At the purely physical level, all the attributes that applied to an analog signal, still apply to a digital one.

As a testament to router reliability, the audio digital router that went to Lake Placid for the 1980 Olympics, was shipped to ABC's Hollywood lot, and was in daily use until 2006. That router could move digital audio 2000 feet on the Hollywood lot.

