Are any 7000s still in use?
*************************************************

Today the routers that Grass Valley offers are not even Grass Valley designs. As we will see the company became so homogenized that a good part of product manufacturing is done in Canada today, and a lot of the current products were designed by companies that subsequent parent companies forced the Group to merge with.

When it comes to routers today, the dedicated television router, that is one that handles baseband audio and video, is starting to go away. In the future video and audio, media, will be routed as IP traffic. In addition with ever increasing clock speeds, the industry was coming up to an inflection point, where new traditional routers would have to be designed from scratch. Over the years routers have gotten so complicated that to design a new one would be a major development effort. The motherboard on the company's latest television router offering, the 8576, a 20 year old design, is a quarter inch thick and it has 38 layers. All components on this board have 5/1000th of an inch tolerance. The company that originally offered this router was NVISION, which, as already mentioned, was the only spin off the company ever had. At that, it still ended up back in the fold! We will visit NVISION later.
